1. Introduction¶

Go back to the "Table of contents"

Marine data plays a critical role in Africa, a continent where oceanic and climatic dynamics significantly impact economies, ecosystems, and livelihoods. With over 26,000 km of coastline, Africa relies on its marine resources for fisheries, transportation, energy, and biodiversity conservation. Furthermore, climate variability and extreme weather events—such as tropical storms, coastal erosion, and rising sea levels—necessitate accurate ocean monitoring to better anticipate their effects and develop adaptive strategies. Understanding oceanic conditions is essential for sustainable development, disaster risk management, and the long-term resilience of coastal communities.

One of the most influential climatic systems affecting West Africa is the West African Monsoon (WAM), which governs rainfall patterns and directly influences agriculture, food security, and both terrestrial and marine ecosystems. This system results from complex interactions between the Atlantic Ocean and atmospheric circulation over the Sahara. A key factor in its variability is the Gulf of Guinea, where sea surface temperature fluctuations can modulate the monsoon’s intensity and distribution. Warmer or cooler waters in this region can shift rainfall patterns, potentially causing droughts or floods with significant socio-economic consequences.

Studying long-term trends in key oceanic variables—such as sea surface temperature, salinity, ocean currents, and atmospheric pressure—can provide invaluable insights into climate change impacts and natural variability in the region. By analyzing historical data, scientists can detect patterns that influence the monsoon system and predict future climatic shifts with greater accuracy. This long-term perspective is crucial for improving climate models, enhancing early warning systems, and informing policies on coastal protection, fisheries management, and sustainable development. In a rapidly changing climate, investing in sustained marine observations will be essential for building resilience and ensuring the well-being of millions of people who depend on West Africa’s coastal and oceanic resources.

</center>
Schematic view of the West African Monsoon System adopted from Lafore et al. (2010). FIT stands for ITD (InterTropical Discontinuity), “Air chaud Saharien” stands for ‘Warm Saharian Air”, JEA stands for AEJ (African Easterly Jet), JET stands for TEJ (Tropical Easterly Jet), “Air sec” stands for “Dry Air”. - From Sylla et al

In this notebook, we will focus on sea water temperature, ocean currents, and primary production. We will analyse how these variables interact with each other and what are the long-term trends associated with them.

3. Data¶

Go back to the "Table of contents"

3.1 Presentation of the product used¶

Go back to the "Table of contents"

We will derive the sea water temperature and the currents from a reanalysis product from the CMEMS catalogue : Global Ocean Physics Reanalysis.

This system mainly relies on the real-time global forecasting model from CMEMS. It uses the NEMO platform, which is driven at the surface by ECMWF ERA-Interim data, later replaced by ERA5 for recent years. Observations are incorporated using a simplified Kalman filter. It assimilates data from satellite altimeters (Sea Level Anomaly), Sea Surface Temperature, Sea Ice Concentration, and in-situ temperature and salinity profiles. Additionally, a 3D-VAR scheme helps correct slow-developing large-scale biases in temperature and salinity.

The table below summarizes the main characteristics of the dataset :

Parameter Value
Variables used thetao, uo, vo
Product identifier GLOBAL_MULTIYEAR_PHY_001_030
Spatial resolution 0.083° × 0.083°
Temporal resolution Daily, Monthly
Temporal coverage 1 Jan 1993 to 28 Jan 2025

In our case, we will only download monthly data. It will allow us to study the trends across the 30 years of data available, while maintaining manageable file sizes.

For detailed information about the product, please consult the document: Product User Manual (PUM)

For information about the quality of the product, please consult the document: Quality Information Document (QUID)

We will derive the primary production from satellite observations : Global Ocean Colour Plankton MY L4 monthly observations.

This productis derived from multiple satellite data inputs : SeaWiFS, MODIS, MERIS, VIIRS-SNPP, OLCI-S3A and OLCI-S3B.

The table below summarizes the main characteristics of the dataset :

Parameter Value
Variables used CHL
Product identifier OCEANCOLOUR_GLO_BGC_L4_MY_009_108
Spatial resolution 4 x 4 km
Temporal resolution Monthly
Temporal coverage 1 Sep 1997 to 1 Dec 2024

For detailed information about the product, please consult the document: Product User Manual (PUM)

For information about the quality of the product, please consult the document: Quality Information Document (QUID)

3.2 Accessing the data : the Copernicus ToolBox¶

Go back to the "Table of contents"

The Copernicus Marine Toolbox a new free tool that allows users to explore product metadata information, subset datasets, and download original files from producers, all without quotas. The procedure of downloading Copernicus Marine products is explained in details here. The data needed for the training is entirely downloadable using the following Python cells.

In this section, we will show you the downloading process of the Sea-Ice product by subsetting a specific region, variable, and period of time with the help of subset function of the Toolbox.

First, we import the Toolbox. Make sure to have activated the pre-installed CMEMS Python Kernel v4, which contains the Toolbox library. You can select it by clicking at the top right hand corner of this window.

The dataset has 4 dimensions : depth, latitude, longitude and time. However, we retrieved only one depth level from the product : 0.5 meters beneath the surface. It is therefore nos use to keep this "depth" dimension in the dataset. To simplify an xarray dataset that has dimensions with single levels, use the squeeze method.

ds = ds.squeeze()

To complete our dataset, we cill compute the total current velocity by combining the eastward and northward components, using the following formula :


Current Speed= $\sqrt{uo²+vo²}$











In [10]:



     


ds['cur_speed'] = np.sqrt(ds.uo**2 + ds.vo**2)



     















In order to highlight seasonal patterns, one thing we can do is compute 4 different climatologies over the 27 years of data available : for Summer, Fall, Winter and Spring. In order to do this, it is possible to compute the seasonal means of the dataset using only the groupby function. Xarray will automatically group together winter months, summer months, etc.











In [12]:



     


ds_seas = ds.groupby("time.season").mean()
ds_seas

The time coordinate has been replaced by a "season" coordinate, with 4 values : DJF (December Janury February : Winter), JJA (June July August : Summer), MAM (March April May : Spring), SON (September October November  : Fall).


Lets visualize the computed climatologies.











In [13]:



     


# display seasonal current patterns

f = plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))


seasons = ["DJF", "MAM", "JJA", "SON"]

ds_seas_coarse = ds_seas.coarsen(latitude=5, longitude=5, boundary="trim").mean()
x = ds_seas_coarse.longitude.data
y = ds_seas_coarse.latitude.data

for c, season in enumerate(seasons):

    ax = plt.subplot(2,2,c+1, projection = ccrs.PlateCarree())
    ax.coastlines()
    ax.add_feature(cfeature.LAND, zorder=1, edgecolor='k')                            
    ax.add_feature(cfeature.BORDERS, linestyle=':')
    ax.set_extent([lon_min, lon_max, lat_min, lat_max])
    gl = ax.gridlines(crs=ccrs.PlateCarree(), draw_labels=True)
    gl.right_labels = False                                                            
    gl.top_labels = False 
    ax.set_ylabel('Latitude (°)')
    ax.set_ylabel('Longitude (°)')
    
    im = ax.pcolor(ds_seas.longitude.data, ds_seas.latitude.data, ds_seas.sel(season=season).thetao.data, cmap='jet', vmin=25, vmax=30)
    cbar = f.colorbar(im, ax=ax,fraction=0.02, pad=0.02)                                            # add the colorbar
    cbar.set_label('SST (°C)', rotation=270,fontsize=15, labelpad=25)
    ax.set_title(f'{season}')
    
    qv = ax.quiver(x, y, ds_seas_coarse.sel(season=season)["uo"], ds_seas_coarse.sel(season=season)["vo"], pivot='mid', angles='xy')

plt.tight_layout()



     


















    
    



























On the plots, the arrows show the currents and the colors show the Sea Surface Temperature. We can see a clear cooling phenomenon during boreal summer, especially near the coast.


During the boreal summer (June–September), the West African Monsoon intensifies, and the southeast trade winds strengthen along the equator. These winds push surface waters away from the coast due to Ekman transport, a process where the wind-driven movement of water layers causes surface waters to be deflected offshore. Therefore, deeper (and colder) waters rise to replace the displaced water.

We have computed correlation along the time coordinate. Therefore our result is a correlation map : with a correlation coefficient between SST and current velocity for each pixel. Let's visualize this.

There is a strong inverse correlation between SST and current speed near the coast (area in dark red) : this highlights the idea that strong currents in this area tend to bring colder waters to the surface, confirming that current-driven upwelling is a key factor in SST variability in this region. Other areas show weaker negative or positive correlations, which may indicate the influence of other processes.

7. Long Term Trends in the West African Moonsoon System¶
Go back to the "Table of contents"


In this sections, we analyse whether or not the ocean variables in the Gulf of Guinea. We will look at the trends in SST, current velocity, and chlorophyll-a concentration. This will allow us to evaluate the potentials impacts of climate change in the region: potential rise of the temperatures, shifting of the current dynamics and variations in biomass.











In order to highlight long-term trends, we can smooth out the seasonal pattern of the data by resampling the monthly dataset and compute the yearly means of SSt current speed, and chl-a concentrations. We can either use the groupby or the resample functions from xarray.











In [19]:



     


ds_avg_y = ds.mean(dim=['latitude','longitude']).groupby('time.year').mean()
ds_chl_avg_y = ds_chl.groupby("time.year").mean().mean(dim=['latitude','longitude'], skipna = True)



     















7.1 Current Dynamics¶
Go back to the "Table of contents"


Using the linear regression module from scipy, we now compute the linear trends for the current variables : horizontal component, vertical component and total speed. The linregress function will also yield the correlation coefficient and p-value to evaluate the significance of the trend. You can read the associated documentation to know more about the function and its outputs.











In [20]:



     


slope1, intercept1, r1, p1, se1 = linregress(ds_avg_y.year.data,  ds_avg_y.cur_speed.data)
slope2, intercept2, r2, p2, se2 = linregress(ds_avg_y.year.data,  ds_avg_y.uo.data)
slope3, intercept3, r3, p3, se3 = linregress(ds_avg_y.year.data,  ds_avg_y.vo.data)

trend_vals1 = ds_avg_y.year.data*slope1 + intercept1
trend_vals2 = ds_avg_y.year.data*slope2 + intercept2
trend_vals3 = ds_avg_y.year.data*slope3 + intercept3



     















In [21]:



     


fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))

ax1 = plt.subplot(221)
ax1.plot(ds_avg_y.year.data, ds_avg_y.uo.data, color='k')
ax1.plot(ds_avg_y.year.data, trend_vals2, color='b', linestyle=':', label='%.1f $mm.s^{-1}.{y^-1}$' % (1000*slope2))
ax1.set_title('Eastward Velocity\nTrend Correlation Coef : r= %.2f' %r2)

We can see that although both components seem to show declining speed over the years, the total speed doesn't undergo any significant changes. Looking more closely at the plots we observe that the variabilities of the two components compensate each other, therefore we cannot conclude on a weakening or strengthening of the current velocity in the Gulf of Guinea.











7.2 Sea Surface Temperatures¶

slope, intercept, r, p, se = linregress(ds_chl_avg_y.year.data,  ds_chl_avg_y.CHL.data)

ax.set_ylabel('$mg.m^{-3}$')

There is a sharp decline in 2010, followed by stable but low concentration values. This may suggest, especially given the gradual rise of SST, that temperatures passed a critical threshold that strongly decreased primary production, with potential impacts on local fisheries. However, more precesses could be at work (Atlantic Niño, or changes in the West African Monsoon) and they should also be investigated, over a longer period of time, to better understand this shift in primary production.
